<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-411-568  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 411 568.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computergram International  July 6 1989 n1214* Full Text COPYRIGHT Apt Data Services 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Empirical launches device driver, text retrieval software.andO;(Empirical Research) (product announcement)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Empirical Research (product introduction).andO;Product:   Unix Driver Guru (Computer program) (product introduction)Minds (Computer program) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Device DriversProgram Development ToolsText Data BasesSoftware PackagesProduct Introduction.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>EMPIRICAL LAUNCHES DEVICE DRIVER, TEXT RETRIEVAL SOFTWAREandM;US software house Empirical Research has set up a UK base in Lichfield,Staffordshire, and is introducing two Unix products on to the market.andP;  TheUnix Driver Guru is effectively a book on disk for Unix programmers, whichprovides information on writing or modifying Unix device drivers, from anoverview of design right down to technical information on specific systemcalls and functions.andP;  Examples of device drivers are included on the disk forSCSI, input-output, liquid crystal display, and a high speed disk controllerdevice driver for VME/SMD interface boards.andP;  Unix Driver Guru costs #95 andruns on MS-DOS machines, and Empirical has sold 15 of the disks in the UKsince the European Unix User Show earlier this month, and over 200 have nowbeen sold in the US.andP;  Also new from Empirical is Minds - a text retrievalsystem developed by US firm Terus.andP;  Files of ASCII text are indexed - withoutthe need for complex preparation - and Minds can then be interrogated usingplain language questions.andP;  Minds for MS-DOS cost #100, Unix System V.3.2versions range in price from #550 to #1,500 depending on configuration, and aversion targeted at Xenix is also under development.andO;</TEXT></DOC>